      <text>7.4.5.3 (not in quiz): Determinant method â”€ Inverse of a 3 x 3 matrix</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p></p><p>Use the determinant method to find the inverse of the following matrices</p>
<p>\[\bf A = {@A@},\] \[\bf B = {@B@}.\]</p>
<div>(a) \(\bf A^{-1}=\) [[input:ans1]].</div><div><br></div><p>[[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]<br></p>
<div>(b) \(\bf B^{-1}=\) [[input:ans2]].</div><p>[[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p></p><p><b>FEEDBACK</b></p><p>To find the inverse of \(\bf A = {@A@}\) using the determinant method will require four steps.</p><p>First we find the determinant of \(\bf A.\)</p><p>\[ \det(\bf A) = {@detA@} .\]</p><p>Since \(\det(\bf A) \neq 0\) the inverse of \(\bf A\) exists.</p><p>Now, we replace each element of \(\bf A\) by its cofactor.</p><p>The cofactor of \({\bf A}_{ij}\) is the determinant of the matrix that remains when row \(i\) and column \(j\) are removed, multiplied by \((-1)^{i+j}\). So we have,</p><p>{@cofactorsA@}.</p><p>Then we transpose the result to obtain the adjoint matrix:<br></p><p>\(\bf adj(A) =&nbsp;{@cofactorsA@}^{T} = {@adjA@}.\)</p><p>Finally we obtain \(\bf A^{-1}\) using the following formula:<br></p><p>\(\bf A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\det(A)} adj(A) = \frac{1}{@detA@} {@adjA@} = {@ta1@}.\)</p><p>The method can be used to determine \(\bf B^{-1}\)&nbsp;similarly, which gives \(B^{-1} = {@ta2@}.\)</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
